{
  "texts": [
    "We evaluate LLMs across multiple random relabelings of the same graph: we draw N = 10 random ℓ's and apply them on the Erdős test graphsfoot_2, and then assess: (a) the mean accuracy over these relabelings; (b) the variability of the models' outputs on numerical tasks.",
    "As for (a), fig. 6 in the Appendix reports the accuracy difference between the original Erdős dataset and sampled node relabelings across tasks.",
    "We observe a clear sensitivity to the relabeling for some tasks, which is more pronounced for G1's than for the original Qwen's.",
    "This can be explained by reliance on positional regularities: certain labelings make the target solution easier for the model to \"heuristically guess\", e.g., in bipartite_maximum_matching, the correct solution in Erdős always induces a contiguous bipartition, i.e., ({1,..., x}, {x + 1,..., n}) for some x. Finetuning can internalize this heuristic, but after relabeling blocks cease to be contiguous and performance drops.",
    "As for (b), we capture output variability induced by node relabelings by calculating the normalized output span averaged over all test graphs in numerical tasks-a value of 0.0 indicates no variability, as desired for invariance."
  ]
}